english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Park, Keeper of the Laws
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Among the Park clan of Ninghai, those who gained prominence in the world through mastery of classical learning and administrative service—there was one called Park Won-gye, Minister of Law. In the time of King Chungsuk, an envoy came from the capital, relying on royal favor to make trouble. He brought a matter of slaves before the king, seeking to twist justice to his own advantage. Twice he pressed his case at the palace gates, and the king ordered his ministers to settle it. Minister Park, then serving as Censor, distinguished right from wrong without wavering. The envoy departed in great anger. The king then said, "This is how a minister should be," and promoted him to Executive Censor to honor his uprightness. The age was impressed.

    When the Minister was nineteen, in the year of Ssinchuk, Commandant Jeong brought scholars to the National Academy. Yi Ik-jae, at fifteen years, topped the examination, and our Minister came second. That year, when Kwon Pu of the Kukjae and Cho Kan of the Yulheon conducted the civil service examinations, the Minister passed again.

    As Recorder of Jeonju, he also served as keeper of records. A tiger terrorized the region, and neither the provincial governor nor his officials could capture it. The task fell to the Minister, who stationed archers at the narrow passes and brought down the beast with a single arrow.

    He served as provisional keeper of the Imperial Library, then moved to become Rector of the National Academy. That winter he entered the Hall of Worthies as Inspector. He followed King Chungseon to the court at Yan, standing at his side with brush in hand, so careful and diligent that he earned the king's deep affection.

    He became Deputy Administrator of Kaan, then Chamberlain at the Inner Gate, then served in the Ministry of Works. In the summer of the year Gapja, as Minor Administrator of Kaesung, he governed Boseong County with benevolence. In the autumn of Shimsin, he became Minister of Rites. In the spring of Eul-hae, he rose to Keeper of Rites and Censor, greatly strengthening discipline and order in the court.

    The following year, he was promoted to Vice-Counselor. Later he became Keeper of the Royal Genealogy and Drafter of Edicts. In spring of Muin, he took charge of the Minor Treasury while maintaining his rank as Doctor and Keeper of the Archive. He was selected as Commissioner of Kangnung Province. When autumn came and he was to return, the Prime Minister said, "The people of Kangnung are content under Commissioner Park," and sent an emissary with provisions to ask him to stay. This happened again in spring, and again in autumn. Even now the people of that region remember him with longing.

    When King Chungae took the throne in the year Gyeongchin, a Board for Popular Welfare was established, and the Minister served as its chief commissioner for two years. His decisions were fair and balanced, earning universal praise.

    When King Chungjeong began his reign, he greatly employed talented men. Those who selected officials valued the Law Ministry, finding few worthy of it. Thus they appointed the Minister, elevating him to Grand Counselor and Keeper of the Archive. All at court said, "The post of Minister of Law has found its true holder at last."

    That year, the Minister was sixty-seven. In the fourth month, on the twelfth day, he fell ill. On the twenty-third day, he passed away. He was buried in the valley of Ma-jeon on Yangchok Mountain at Tongsung, in the ninth year of Zhizhen, the year Gimchuk. In the first month of the year Eulmi, his wife, Lady O, passed from illness. She too was buried in the same place.

    Lady O came from Duwon and was the daughter of Court Attendant Righteous. She kept her household with dignity and taught her children with proper measure. She bore two sons: Bao-sheng, who became Commander of the Guard, and Tong-sheng, now Minister of Works. Their daughter married Kim Dae-gyeong, Inspector of the National Academy.

    The Minister's first wife was the daughter of Counselor Yi Ik-jae, and bore him three sons: Gyeong, who became Vice-President of the Three Excellencies; Wei, an inspector of the Imperial Library; and Su-mun, a general. His second wife was the daughter of retired administrator Chae Ja, by whom he had one younger son.

    When I was yet young and the Minister visited our household, I saw in him a robust frame and heard in his words a gentle kindness, and knew not his stern virtue. As I grew older and learned that he had served as Censor and Inspector, I came to understand that here was a man of unyielding principle. After his passing, I long regretted that I had not studied at his side longer, and grieved that such aged wisdom had departed from us.

    His son, the Minister of Works, passed the advanced examination and became a great talent of his age. Rising with distinction into the provincial government, wherever he went he left the memory of benevolent rule. Thus when he requested this epitaph, I did not refuse, but recorded his family line and composed this verse:

    In the corner of the eastern sea
    Our Minister was born.
    From Danyang's domain
    He flew forth on the highway bright.

    He served our King Chungseon,
    Brush in hand at the court of Yan.
    Under glorious King Chungsuk
    He ruled within arm's reach.

    At the palace gates, judging disputes,
    He separated black from white.
    Raised then to Vice-Counselor,
    The nation's guardian of justice.

    As Commissioner of Kangnung,
    He ascended mountains, crossed the seas.
    One region dwelt in peace—
    Not by my power alone,
    But through long years of stewardship,
    Culture flourished and took root.

    Where lawsuits ceased, there honor dwelt,
    The Chief of the Censorate in truth.
    Though his work remained incomplete,
    And yellow earth has claimed him now,
    This epitaph is not mere sentiment—
    It is the record of the Grand Historian.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Ik-jae (李益齋) was a renowned scholar-official of the Goryeo period, known for his virtue and learning. The Minister's second place in the examination after Yi Ik-jae was considered a great honor.
  - key: ''
    value: King Chungseon's court at Yan (燕) refers to the Mongol capital, where the Goryeo court maintained close relations during the Yuan dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The epitaph follows the traditional form of Chinese commemorative writing, combining biographical narrative with a concluding poem that celebrates the subject's virtue and service.
